<project_context>

Project Name:
SimplyDSE

Project Type:
Enterprise Multi-Tenant SaaS Platform

Core Purpose:
A DSE (Display Screen Equipment) assessment and compliance management platform for organizations.

Primary Users:
- HR Teams
- Compliance Officers
- Operations Teams
- Health & Safety Teams
- Enterprise Organizations
- Government Organizations

Core Features:
- DSE assessments
- Employee management
- Compliance tracking
- Risk monitoring
- Reporting dashboards
- Workflow automation
- Audit logging
- Role-based access control
- Notifications/reminders
- Analytics
- Multi-tenant organization system
- Wildcard subdomain support

This platform should feel like:
- modern enterprise software
- operational infrastructure
- a trusted daily-use platform

NOT:
- a startup hype product
- a cinematic experience
- an animation showcase
</project_context>

<technology_stack>

Frontend:
- Next.js
- React
- TypeScript
- Tailwind CSS
- shadcn/ui
- Framer Motion (minimal use only)

Backend:
- NestJS
- TypeScript

Database:
- PostgreSQL

ORM:
- Prisma

Infrastructure:
- Redis
- BullMQ
- Cloudflare-compatible architecture

Authentication:
- enterprise RBAC architecture
- tenant-aware authentication
- organization-scoped sessions

Architecture Type:
- multi-tenant SaaS
- tenant_id-based architecture
- scalable modular systems

DO NOT:
- recommend WordPress
- recommend Firebase-style architecture
- build CMS-first systems
- generate plugin-dependent architecture
</technology_stack>

<frontend_architecture>

Frontend architecture must be:
- modular
- scalable
- component-driven
- maintainable
- enterprise-oriented

Preferred structure:
- reusable UI components
- feature-based architecture
- scalable routing
- shared design tokens
- typed API integrations
- clean folder organization

Avoid:
- monolithic pages
- deeply nested chaos
- duplicated UI patterns
- ad-hoc styling
- random utility clutter
</frontend_architecture>

<design_system_rules>

The design philosophy is:

clarity > creativity

The interface should feel:
- premium
- calm
- operational
- trustworthy
- efficient
- modern
- realistic
- enterprise-grade

Design inspirations:
- Linear
- Stripe Dashboard
- Ramp
- Retool
- Notion
- Vercel Dashboard
- modern B2B SaaS systems

DO NOT:
- over-design
- over-animate
- create cinematic sections
- create giant hero layouts
- use excessive gradients
- use visual gimmicks
- create unrealistic concept dashboards
- prioritize decoration over usability

The UI should prioritize:
- readability
- hierarchy
- spacing consistency
- operational workflows
- data clarity
- realistic enterprise patterns
</design_system_rules>

<animation_rules>

Animations must be:
- subtle
- restrained
- performant
- purposeful

Allowed:
- small fades
- smooth transitions
- micro-interactions
- light hover effects

Avoid:
- floating chaos
- cinematic scroll animations
- exaggerated motion
- heavy parallax
- distracting transitions
- startup-style hero animations

Motion should enhance usability —
NOT dominate the experience.
</animation_rules>

<dashboard_rules>

Dashboard interfaces are CRITICAL.

Dashboard UX must prioritize:
- fast scanning
- operational clarity
- dense but readable information
- responsive layouts
- realistic workflows
- efficient navigation

Dashboard components should include:
- metrics cards
- compliance summaries
- activity feeds
- alerts
- employee tables
- assessment workflows
- reporting panels
- audit logs
- organization switching
- role-based views

Dashboards should feel:
- clean
- structured
- stable
- trustworthy

NOT:
- flashy
- decorative
- conceptual
</dashboard_rules>

<layout_rules>

Spacing and layout consistency are VERY important.

The interface should:
- avoid giant empty sections
- avoid excessive scrolling
- avoid oversized hero sections
- fit content efficiently
- maintain clean rhythm and spacing

Preferred characteristics:
- balanced whitespace
- structured grids
- realistic SaaS proportions
- scalable page systems

Hero sections should:
- communicate clearly
- fit comfortably within viewport
- avoid cinematic proportions
- focus on trust and product clarity

Preferred tone:
clear → trustworthy → professional

NOT:
artistic → oversized → dramatic
</layout_rules>

<component_rules>

Components must be:
- reusable
- scalable
- typed
- accessible
- composable
- production-ready

Prefer:
- shadcn/ui patterns
- clean abstraction
- variant-driven systems
- reusable cards/tables/modals/forms

Avoid:
- one-off components
- duplicated patterns
- over-complicated abstractions
- inconsistent styling systems
</component_rules>

<multi_tenant_architecture>

This platform MUST support multi-tenancy.

Every major data model should support:
- tenant_id
- organization ownership
- scoped access
- role-aware permissions

Example tenant structure:

acme.simplydse.com
govagency.simplydse.com
enterprise.simplydse.com

The architecture must support:
- tenant-aware routing
- tenant-scoped APIs
- isolated organization data
- scalable RBAC
- organization-specific dashboards

Tenant isolation is CRITICAL.
</multi_tenant_architecture>

<security_rules>

Always think with enterprise security principles.

Prioritize:
- RBAC enforcement
- tenant isolation
- secure session handling
- protected API routes
- audit logging
- scalable auth boundaries
- permission-aware architecture

Avoid:
- insecure shared access logic
- weak auth assumptions
- exposing tenant data
- tightly coupled auth systems
</security_rules>

<development_workflow>

Development workflow priorities:
1. plan architecture first
2. build scalable foundations
3. create reusable systems
4. maintain consistency
5. refine UX carefully
6. optimize readability
7. preserve maintainability

When generating code:
- think long-term
- think production-scale
- think enterprise maintainability

DO NOT:
- optimize for shortcuts
- generate messy structure
- prioritize speed over architecture
- create temporary hacks
</development_workflow>

<code_quality_rules>

Code must be:
- typed
- modular
- maintainable
- readable
- production-grade

Use:
- TypeScript best practices
- clean naming conventions
- scalable folder organization
- reusable utilities
- proper separation of concerns

Avoid:
- giant files
- unclear naming
- duplicated logic
- fragile architecture
- tightly coupled components
</code_quality_rules>

<final_behavior_rules>

Always behave like:
- an enterprise SaaS engineering team
